Like weaving together heritage and heart to integrate Filipino culture into a documentary style wedding photographerâ€™s brand.

@samahanstudio branding remains one of the most intentional designs to date (especially as a part Filipina creative, myself).

The subtle hand drawn banig texture is one of many thought out and intentional choices to bring Celeneâ€™s family heritage into a tastefully crafted brand.

A banig is a traditional Filipino handwoven mat that are staples in our homes. From sleeping mats to sitting or decoration, they represent a lineage of hand weaving skills and intentional craft.

Which in addition to the Filipino heritage, also represents Celeneâ€™s eye for detail deeply rooted in her empathy.

The detail-ception goes deep.
And our communities felt seen.

Did you know that hoodies and T-shirts have played a pivotal role in social movements worldwide? In the 1970s, the hoodie became a symbol of anonymity and rebellion, often associated with the hip-hop culture in New York. Meanwhile, T-shirts have been used as canvases for political statements and art since the 1960s, making them powerful tools for expression and change. These garments have transcended fashion, becoming iconic symbols of identity and resistance across the globe.

At Outcast Apparel, we embrace this rich history by offering hoodies and T-shirts that let you express your unique story and stand out in the crowd!

adidas Y-3 Gendo Superstar (Black, Size 10.5)

When Yohji Yamamoto first partnered with adidas in 2002 to launch Y-3, it redefined how sportswear and high fashion could intersect. Two decades later, the Gendo Superstar pushed that vision into radical new territory.

Unveiled during Paris Fashion Week in 2022, the Gendo transformed the iconic adidas Superstar into a piece of wearable architecture. The shoe retained its leather upper and shell-toe heritage, but sat atop a hollowed-out, sculptural plate designed to â€œelevateâ€ the wearer â€” literally and conceptually. Its open-arch platform blurred the line between sneaker and object, a bold experiment that drew coverage from Highsnobiety, Hypebeast, and Vogue, with headlines framing it as one of the most daring sneaker designs of the year.

The Gendo Superstar wasnâ€™t made for mass wear. Its limited release, avant-garde silhouette, and high price point made it instantly polarizing â€” celebrated by collectors of Yohji Yamamotoâ€™s work and fashion-forward sneakerheads, while bewildering traditionalists. Today, it stands as one of the most striking examples of Y-3â€™s philosophy: challenging expectations while preserving the DNA of adidasâ€™ most iconic sneaker.
